national policy -- t10 From research to a national curriculum: The case of a lexical syllabus -- t11 Tensions in collaborative research with teachers in the context of language education policy change in Finland -- t12 National graduate schools in language education: Dimensions of collaboration and reciprocity -- tAfterword -- t13 An ethical perspective on collaborative research -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLanguage education at all levels benefits from research in a multitude of ways. Conversely, educational practices and experiences offer fertile ground for research into language learning, teaching and assessment. This book views research in language education as a reciprocal venture that should benefit all participants equally. Practice is shaped by theory, which in turn is illuminated and refined by practice. The book brings together studies from different fields of language education in nine countries on four continents: Cameroon, Canada, Finland, India, Ireland, Israel, Italy, Japan and Sweden. The authors report on research that depends on the active involvement of teachers, teacher educators and learners of different ages and various backgrounds. The book focuses on projects designed to address challenges in the classroom and on the role of learners as collaborative agents in the research process as well as collaborative research in professional development and the role of collaborative research in the development of national policy.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teachingxResearch. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aEducational Research, Collaboration, Reciprocity, Agency.1 aBardel, Camilla, econtribut